\f0\b\fs50 \cf0 Design optimizations\

\f1\b0\fs24 The design of this pcb is optimized for low power, size, and progammability.
\f0\b\fs50 \
Main MCU - NRF52840\

\f1\b0\fs24 The nRF52840 was chosen because it hits every requirement of this project in a single chip. It has a Cortex-M4 with hardware floating point which is needed for the EKF sensor fusion math. It has native USB built in so no bridge chip is needed for programming. It has BLE 5.0 built in for the future phone integration without adding any external module. Its deep sleep current is around 1.5\'b5A which is critical for a wearable running on a small LiPo. It also has an internal DC-DC converter that can be enabled in firmware to improve power efficiency further. The nRF52840 is the same chip used in the Seeed XIAO dev board already validated for this project, meaning the firmware toolchain, libraries, and IMU drivers are already familiar. No other single chip combines low power, native USB, BLE, and sufficient processing headroom for motion algorithms at this price point and package size.\
\
The chip also has internal regulator; it can accept up to 5V5 on its VDDH pin and internally step down to 3V3 for internal use and external power. So no LDO is actually needed on this board because of it.\
\
I went with the QFN-73 variant even though all 73 pins weren\'92t needed (mcu will only support IMU and LCD). The nRF52840 comes in two QFN packages - QFN73 (7x7mm) and QFN48 (6x6mm). The QFN48 was rejected immediately because it has no USB pins - D+, D-, and VBUS are all absent. Since this design relies on USB for drag-and-drop firmware flashing and for detecting when the charger is plugged in, the QFN48 is a hard no regardless of its smaller size. The 1mm size difference on each side is irrelevant on a 42mm PCB anyway. QFN73 it is, LCSC part C190794.\
\
The baseline design was followed by Nordic\'92s documentation: https://docs.nordicsemi.com/bundle/ps_nrf52840/page/pin.html\
For the QFN73 there are 7 different configurations to follow based on your circuitry. I followed the one that allows features as:\
Selected: Config 4 (QIAA aQFN73) \
\
VDDH = Battery/Ext. regulator (PMIC output) The PMIC output (sourced from either USB or LiPo depending on what's plugged in) feeds directly into VDDH. This puts the chip in High Voltage mode, meaning the internal REG0 regulator handles stepping the input voltage down internally. No external LDO required.\
 VDD = N/A In High Voltage mode VDD is an output, not an input. The internal REG0 regulator produces the regulated 3.3V on this pin. Left unconnected from any external supply. \
EXTSUPPLY = Yes The regulated 3.3V on VDD is exposed to power external components \'97 specifically the LSM6DSV IMU (0.65mA max) and the display. \
DCDCEN0 must be enabled for this to work reliably given the current draw of the display. DCDCEN0 = Yes Enables the internal DC-DC switching converter for REG0 instead of the internal LDO. This raises the maximum current the chip can supply externally beyond the 25mA LDO limit, and is more efficient \'97 it draws less from the battery for the same output. Requires one external 10\'b5H inductor on the DCCH pin. This is the only extra passive component this config adds. \
DCDCEN1 = No The REG1 DC-DC converter (which powers the chip core from VDD) is left disabled for v1 simplicity. REG1 runs as internal LDO instead. Can be enabled in a future revision for further efficiency gains. \
USB = Yes D+ and D- are wired to the USB-C connector for firmware flashing. \
VBUS is connected to the USB-C 5V line so the chip can detect when USB is plugged in and trigger the appropriate power and charging events in firmware. NFC = No NFC pins left unconnected. Not used in v1 or v2.\
\
AD2 VBUS - It's just a sense/detection pin with its own isolated internal regulator. You wire it to VBUS on the USB-C connector (5V)\
AD14 VDD - in Config 4 VDD is an output. It's your 3.3V rail that goes to: IMU (VDD pin on LSM6DSV) Display (VCC pin) Any other 3.3V peripherals And it also has decoupling caps to GND on each VDD pin of the nRF52840 itself \'97 the datasheet specifies 100nF on each one, placed as close to the pin as physically possible on the PCB. So on schematic VDD is just a net label "3V3" that connects to everything that needs 3.3V.\
