Design notes:\
Datasheet mentions 3 possible interface connections. Mode 1 was selected which is MCU communicating to IMU via I2C. Other modes are not relevant as they treat the IMU as a master \
\
	SD0/SA0 - Connected to GND to set 0x6A address\
	CS - pulled to 3V3 - data sheet does not state requirement of a resistor , cant find out if there is an internal pull-up\
	SDX/SCX - no use case in mode 1 - option was either connect to VDD_IO (HIGH) or GND (LOW). Pulled to GND.\
	INT1/INT2 - programmable interrupt. INT1 routed to GPIO for ability to implement it in firmware. INT2 left floating.\
				this will be used for the LSM6DSV can be configured to generate an interrupt when motion is detected, waking the nRF52840 from deep sleep. This is critical for battery life on a wearable. \
				The flow would be: Device idle \uc0\u8594  nRF52840 in deep sleep (1.5\'b5A), IMU in low power mode User starts moving \u8594  IMU detects motion \u8594  pulls INT1 high \u8594  wakes nRF52840 instantly nRF52840 starts 				sampling and counting reps User stops \u8594  back to sleep Without INT1 connected you'd have to poll the IMU constantly which kills battery life. With it connected you get essentially free wake-on-motion. 				Configure it as an input with interrupt in firmware. Connected to P1.06\
	SDO_AUX/OCS_AUX - not a feature In mode 1; left floating as per data sheet 
