\f0\b\fs50 \cf0 \
PMIC\

\f1\b0\fs26 BQ24074 - USB charger with smart power path management\
Selectable 100mA and 500mA max input current, 100mA max current limit ensures compliance to USB-IF standard\
\
From the datasheet page 6, the EN1/EN2 pins offer four modes: both low gives USB100 (100mA input limit), \
											EN1 high EN2 low gives USB500 (500mA input limit), \
											EN1 low EN2 high gives resistor-programmable mode via ILIM pin, and both high puts the device in standby/suspend. \
USB100 was rejected immediately because with a 100mA input limit and 100mA charge current there is zero headroom left for the system load \'97 the nRF52840 alone draws more than that when active. Resistor-programmable and standby are unnecessary complexity for v1. \
USB500 was selected (EN1 high, EN2 low) giving a 500mA input limit from the USB port, which allows 100mA to charge the battery while leaving ~400mA available for the system load consisting of the MCU, IMU, and display \'97 well within what a standard USB port supplies.
\f0\b\fs50 \
BQ24074
\fs26 \

\f1\b0 The bq24074 is a linear Li-Ion charger and power-path management IC from TI's bq2407x family. Its Dynamic Power Path Management (DPPM) simultaneously powers the system and charges the battery from the same input, reducing unnecessary battery cycles and allowing operation with a depleted cell. Charge current, input current limit, and termination threshold are all resistor-programmable. The bq24074 was selected over other family variants for its adjustable termination current (ITERM pin) and wider input voltage range of 4.35\'9610.5V, accommodating unregulated adapters alongside USB. Onboard protections include OVP, thermal regulation, reverse current blocking, and short-circuit detection, all in a 3\'d73mm 16-pin QFN.}